{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Dependencies (STACKED — review with --ref HEAD)\nBuilds on **ddbe** (identity entity with `mappings: [{provider, external_id}]`),\ncommitted on this branch but not yet on origin/main. Review with `--ref HEAD`.\n\n## Context\nResolve outbound Jira assignee/reporter by the provider's opaque **accountId** —\nlooked up through the identity entity's `{provider, external_id}` mappings behind a\nprovider seam — instead of by display-name/email string matching, with graceful\ndegradation when no mapping resolves. Mappings are keyed on the provider's stable\nopaque id, NEVER on email.\n\n## Why\nJira's `/user/assignable/search` does fuzzy/relevance matching on a name/email and\ncan mis-assign (or fail when email is hidden by privacy settings). An identity\ncarrying a `{provider:\"jira\", external_id:<accountId>}` mapping lets the reconciler\nset the assignee by exact accountId, deterministically, and degrade to unassigned /\nproject-default rather than hard-failing.\n\n## What\n### 1. Provider-neutral resolution seam (`src/rebar/_commands/identity.py`)\n- `resolve_mapping(provider: str, external_id: str, *, repo_root=None) -> str | None`\n  — return the id of the identity whose `mappings` contains\n  `{\"provider\": provider, \"external_id\": external_id}` (exact match on the opaque id),\n  else `None`. This is the AC1 provider seam (also consumed inbound by 2f13).\n- `jira_account_id(local_assignee: str, *, repo_root=None) -> str | None` — resolve a\n  LOCAL assignee string to a Jira accountId: find an identity whose ticket id equals\n  `local_assignee` OR whose `email` equals it (case-insensitive); return that\n  identity's `{provider:\"jira\"}` mapping `external_id` (the accountId), else `None`.\n  Never raises.\n\n### 2. Outbound assignee by accountId (`src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/outbound_differ.py`)\nIn `_assignee_resolver(assignee, jira_key)` (the existing local→accountId resolver),\ntry the identity mapping FIRST: if `jira_account_id(assignee)` returns an accountId,\nreturn `(accountId, authoritative=True)` — no Jira search needed. Only when there is\nNO identity mapping fall back to the existing `client.validate_assignee_exists`\nsearch path. Preserve the existing degradation contract: an unresolved assignee\nyields unassigned (or the project default) via the current soft-fail path — 264f\nmust not hard-fail a sync when an assignee cannot be resolved. Also: `acli.update_issue`\n(~line 354) re-resolves any non-empty assignee via `validate_assignee_exists` — so a\nfast-path accountId would be searched a SECOND time and possibly missed. Thread the\nresolved accountId through EXPLICITLY (accountIds are opaque server strings with no\nreliable shape — do NOT shape-detect). `OutboundMutation` is a FROZEN dataclass with\nfixed fields, so carry the signal INSIDE the `fields`/`changed` dict (not a new\ndataclass field): (a) when the fast-path resolves, the differ writes the RESOLVED\naccountId (`acct`) — not the raw local string — into `changed['assignee']`, AND adds\na sentinel `changed['_assignee_is_account_id'] = True`; (b) at the call site\n`dispatch_one.update_one` / `_update_one_scalar_update` POPS `_assignee_is_account_id`\noff the fields before dispatch (so it is never sent to Jira) and passes an explicit\n`assignee_is_account_id=<bool>` kwarg into `client.update_issue`; (c) `update_issue`\nSKIPS `validate_assignee_exists` (submitting the accountId directly) exactly when that\nkwarg is True. Absent the sentinel, behaviour is unchanged (legacy re-resolution).\n\n### 3. `/user/search` bootstrap (best-effort, `acli_rest.py`)\nWhen an identity has an `email` but no `{provider:\"jira\"}` accountId mapping yet, a\nbest-effort `/rest/api/3/user/search?query=<email>` lookup MAY resolve the accountId\nat reconcile time (bootstrapping the mapping). This is best-effort: a hidden email\n(privacy) or no result degrades to the existing search/unassigned path WITHOUT\nfailing the sync.\n\n### 4. Reporter by accountId where permitted\nSet the Jira reporter to the resolved accountId (same `jira_account_id`\nresolution). `reporter` must be added to the outbound field-mapping layer\n(`outbound_fields.py`) AND the dispatch allowlist\n(`dispatch_one.py::_OUTBOUND_BATCH_ALLOWLIST`) or it is silently stripped before\n`apply_handlers` sees it. Set it ONLY where the project grants Modify-Reporter; when it does not (the common case),\nskip setting reporter and record a documented degradation note (do not hard-fail).\nDetect the permission best-effort (a 403/400 on the reporter field is treated as\n\"not granted\" and swallowed).\n\n## Scope\nIn: the `resolve_mapping` / `jira_account_id` seam, the outbound assignee accountId\nfast-path + degradation, the best-effort `/user/search` bootstrap, and reporter-by-\naccountId-where-granted. Out: inbound ghost/placeholder minting (2f13),\nenforcement (3183). Live-Jira behaviour is exercised with a fixture identity + a\nstubbed client (no live calls in tests).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `resolve_mapping(provider, external_id)` returns the identity whose mappings\n  contain that `{provider, external_id}` (keyed on the opaque id, not email) and\n  `None` when absent; a test asserts both.\n- [ ] The reconciler sets the Jira assignee by accountId when the local assignee maps\n  to an identity's `{provider:\"jira\"}` accountId (test: fixture identity + stubbed\n  accountId, assert the mutation carries the accountId and no Jira search was needed),\n  and degrades to unassigned/project-default WITHOUT hard-failing when the assignee\n  resolves to no account (test: assignee with no mapping + a stubbed search miss).\n- [ ] Best-effort `/user/search` bootstrap: when an identity has an `email` but no\n  `{provider:\"jira\"}` accountId mapping, a stubbed `/user/search` that returns an\n  accountId lets the reconciler resolve the assignee by that accountId; a stubbed\n  miss (hidden email) degrades to unassigned WITHOUT failing (test both).\n- [ ] Reporter is set by accountId where Modify-Reporter is granted; where not\n  granted the reconciler skips it and records a STRUCTURED degradation entry in the\n  reconcile result's soft-fail list (a structured entry\n  `{kind: \"outbound-reporter-not-permitted\", jira_key: <key>, field: \"reporter\",\n  reason: <str>}` in the reconcile result's soft-fail list, like the existing\n  assignee-unresolved soft-fails) and does NOT\n  fail; a test with a stubbed permission-denied reporter response asserts that\n  structured entry is present and the sync still succeeds.\n\n## file_impact\n- `src/rebar/_commands/identity.py` (resolve_mapping + jira_account_id seam)\n- `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/outbound_differ.py` (assignee accountId fast-path)\n- `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/acli_rest.py` (best-effort /user/search bootstrap)\n- `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/outbound_fields.py` (reporter field mapping)\n- `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/dispatch_one.py` (add reporter to _OUTBOUND_BATCH_ALLOWLIST)\n- `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/acli.py` (update_issue: skip re-resolving a pre-resolved accountId)\n- `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/apply_handlers.py` (reporter-by-accountId-where-granted + degradation)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783847686733448001,"uuid":"0b2ccf2e-d05f-471d-a969-29f46c52b082"}